Use conditional compilation or the `MAUI` platform-specific service registration pattern:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (which is already platform-filtered by the default `.csproj` ItemGroup globs), so the linker only includes the relevant one per target.

**Alternative (no `#if`):** Place a partial class registration helper in each `Platforms/<OS>/` folder:

```csharp
// Shared: MauiProgram.cs
builder.Services.RegisterNotificationService();

// Platforms/Android/NotificationServiceRegistration.cs
public static partial class ServiceRegistration
{
    public static partial IServiceCollection RegisterNotificationService(this IServiceCollection s)
        => s.AddSingleton<INotificationService, AndroidNotificationService>();
}
```

Repeat the partial for iOS/Windows. This avoids `#if` blocks entirely and keeps `MauiProgram.cs` clean.
